<p>To install these, create a browser bookmark whose "location" is that long nasty <code>javascript:</code> URL. To activate them, click or tap that bookmark while viewing a page you want to dogear.</p>

<h3>Most Desktop Browsers</h3>

<p>Drag and drop the links, or right-click the links and choose to create a new bookmark.</p>

<p>You usually want these on the "bookmark toolbar" or in the menu, so they're easily accessible.</p>

<h3>iOS Safari</h3>

<p>iOS doesn't want you to bookmark javascript URLs by accident, so it adds an extra step: you have to create a normal bookmark, then manually replace its URL. In more detail:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Use the share menu to bookmark <em>this</em> page. Put it in the "favorites" section for easy access.</li>
  <li>Copy the <code>javascript:</code> URL to the clipboard.</li>
  <li>Open your bookmarks and tap "edit".</li>
  <li>Tap the bookmark you just made. Rename it, and replace the current URL with the copied <code>javascript:</code> URL.</li>
</ol>

<p>If you put your bookmarklets in the "favorites" section, the easiest way to activate them is to tap the URL bar; a list of icons will appear, and you can tap the icon for your bookmarklet. You can also activate bookmarklets from the main bookmarks sheet.</p>

<p>Other iOS browsers have their controls in different places, but still use the same "bookmark something random, then replace the name and URL" technique.</p>

<h3>Android Chrome</h3>

<p>Chrome on Android uses the same installation technique as iOS Safari:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Bookmark <em>this</em> page by going to the "‚Ä¶" menu and tapping the star.</li>
  <li>Copy the <code>javascript:</code> URL to the clipboard.</li>
  <li>Open your bookmarks, find the bookmark you made, and edit it; change the name, and replace the current URL with the copied <code>javascript:</code> URL. You can also move the bookmark, if you want.</li>
</ol>

<p>However, <em>activating</em> bookmarklets on Chrome is weird. You must:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Tap the location bar.</li>
  <li>Type part of the bookmarklet's name, so it appears in the list of suggestions.</li>
  <li>Tap the bookmarklet in the suggestions list.</li>
</ol>

<p>For some reason, Chrome <em>doesn't</em> let you activate bookmarklets by tapping them from the bookmarks list; only the location bar suggestions will work. Because of this, you might want to include a unique sequence of letters in your bookmarklet names.</p>

<p>Other Android browsers might do their own things, but if you've gone to the trouble to install a non-default browser on your telephone in the first place, you can probably sort it out.</p>
